'''Gilbert Jean Marco Brul<U+00E9>'''<ref>{{cite journal |last1=McPhee |first1=Jessica |last2=Stauffer |first2=Bob |last3=Goss |first3=Andrea |year=2010 |title=Oil Country |journal= |publisher=Edmonton Oilers |volume=1 |issue=2 |pages=9 |url= |doi= }}</ref> (born January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;1987) is a Canadian professional [[ice hockey]] [[centre (ice hockey)|centre]] currently with the [[Edmonton Oilers]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL). Drafted out of the [[Western Hockey League]] (WHL), Brul<U+00E9> played [[junior ice hockey|major junior]] with the [[Vancouver Giants]] for three seasons. After being named the [[Jim Piggott Memorial Trophy|WHL rookie of the year]] in [[2003<U+2013>04 WHL season|2004]], Brul<U+00E9> was selected as the [[airBC Trophy|WHL playoff MVP]] and [[Ed Chynoweth Trophy|led the Memorial Cup in scoring]], as part of the Giants' [[Ed Chynoweth Cup|WHL championship]]-winning season two years later. Selected sixth overall in the [[2005 NHL Entry Draft]], he began his NHL career with the [[Columbus Blue Jackets]] before being traded to the Oilers prior to the [[2008<U+2013>09 NHL season|2008<U+2013>09 season]]. Internationally, Brul<U+00E9> has represented [[Hockey Canada|Team Canada]] at the [[2004 World U-17 Hockey Challenge]] and [[2004 U-18 Junior World Cup]], winning silver and gold medals, respectively.

==Playing career==
===Early junior career===
Brul<U+00E9> was selected first overall in the 2002 [[WHL Bantam Draft]] by the [[Vancouver Giants]]. The selection was originally possessed by the [[Prince Albert Raiders]], but was dealt to the Giants in exchange for their third overall and third round selections.<ref>{{Citenews|title=Gilbert Brule selecetd first overall in 2002 WHL Bantam Draft|url=http://www.canoe.ca/WHLNews0102/0503.html|accessdate=2011-02-23|date=2002-05-03|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> He debuted in one game with the Giants during the [[2002<U+2013>03 WHL season|subsequent WHL season]], while playing Junior A{{#tag:ref|Junior A is a competitive level below the major junior level of the Western Hockey League|group=notes}} in the [[British Columbia Hockey League]] (BCHL) with the [[Quesnel Millionaires]]. Recording 57&nbsp;points (32&nbsp;goals and 25&nbsp;assists) over 48&nbsp;games in his lone BCHL season, he was named the Interior Conference's recipient of the Bruce Allison Memorial Trophy as rookie of the year.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Bruce Allison Memorial Trophy|url=http://www.bchl.ca/leagues/custom_page.cfm?leagueID=2393&clientID=1413&pageID=3709|accessdate=2011-03-11|publisher=[[British Columbia Hockey League]]}}</ref>

In [[2003<U+2013>04 WHL season|2003<U+2013>04]], Brul<U+00E9> joined the Giants and tallied 60&nbsp;points in 67&nbsp;games. He became the first Giants player to win a major WHL award,<ref>{{citenews|title=Brule Up For Award/WHL Bantam Draft Approaches|url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/?l_id=113&t_id=1278&id=3027230|accessdate=2010-03-19|date=2004-04-26|publisher=OurSports Central}}</ref> receiving the [[Jim Piggott Memorial Trophy]] as league rookie of the year.<ref name=tsn/> The distinction made him a nominee for [[CHL Rookie of the Year|Canadian Hockey League (CHL) Rookie of the Year]],<ref>{{citenews|title=Crosby among CHL award nominees|url=http://www.tsn.ca/story/print/?id=82056|accessdate=2010-03-19|date=2004-04-29|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}</ref> which went to [[Quebec Major Junior Hockey League]] (QMJHL) rookie of the year [[Sidney Crosby]] of the [[Rimouski Oceanic]].<ref name="chl awards">{{Citeweb|title=CHL Annual Awards|url=http://www.chl.ca/page/awards|accessdate=2011-03-11|publisher=[[Canadian Hockey League]]}}</ref> He joined Crosby on the CHL All-Rookie Team.<ref>{{citenews|title=Macias named to CHL All-Rookie Team|url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/?id=3037518&l_id=&t_id=|accessdate=2010-03-19|date=2004-05-21|publisher=OurSports Central}}</ref>

The [[2004<U+2013>05 WHL season|following season]], Brul<U+00E9> finished third in WHL scoring with 87&nbsp;points (39&nbsp;goals and 48&nbsp;assists),<ref>{{cite web|title=2004-05 Season - All Players|url=http://www.whl.ca/stats/show/type/top_scorers/ls_season/223|accessdate=2011-03-11|publisher=[[Western Hockey League]]}}</ref> establishing a Giants single-season point-scoring record (surpassed by [[Casey Pierro-Zabotel]] in [[2008<U+2013>09 WHL season|2008<U+2013>09]]).<ref>{{citenews|title=Vancouver Giants defeat Medicine Hat in come-from-behind win|url=http://www.vancouversun.com/story_print.html?id=1228884|accessdate=2011-02-03|date=2009-01-28|publisher=''[[The Vancouver Sun]]''}}</ref> During the campaign, he was chosen to a squad of WHL All-Stars against the Russian select team in the 2004 [[ADT Canada-Russia Challenge]] in November.<ref>{{citenews|title=Brule Selected To Play Russians|url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/?id=3099715&l_id=&t_id=|date=2004-11-09|accessdate=2010-03-19|publisher=OurSports Central}}</ref>  Several months later, he competed in the 2005 [[CHL Top Prospects Game]], where he recorded the first [[hat trick]] in the history of the all-star match and was named Team [[Don Cherry|Cherry]]'s player of the game.<ref>{{Citenews|title=Mikkelson and Brule Put Cherry on Top in Prospects Game Victory|url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/?id=3118748|accessdate=2010-03-19|date=2005-01-19|publisher=OurSports Central}}</ref> At the end of the season, Brul<U+00E9> was named the [[CHL Scholastic Player of the Year]], having taken more high school credits than any other WHL player.<ref>{{citenews|title=Crosby repeats as player of the year|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Hockey/Junior/2005/05/25/1055163.html|accessdate=2010-03-19|date=2005-05-25|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|author=Jim Cressman}}</ref>

===NHL debut and Memorial Cup tournament===
Brul<U+00E9> was selected sixth overall in the [[2005 NHL Entry Draft]] by the [[Columbus Blue Jackets]].  He remained the highest-drafted Giants player in team history until [[Evander Kane]] was selected fourth overall in [[2009 NHL Entry Draft|2009]].<ref>{{cite news|title=He was always ahead of schedule|url=http://www.faceoff.com/story.html?id=02972772-5ddc-4918-9ed9-c27cbbf216f0|accessdate=2011-07-20|date=2009-07-28|work=[[The Province]]|location=Vancouver|publisher=CanWest MediaWorks}}</ref> Brul<U+00E9> had been the second-ranked prospect behind Crosby by the International Scouting Services (ISS) at the beginning of the 2004<U+2013>05 season,<ref>{{citenews|title=ISS ranks O'Marra and Blunden top-10 prospects|url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/?id=3088753&l_id=&t_id=|accessdate=2010-03-19|date=2004-09-27|publisher=OurSports Central}}</ref> while the [[NHL Central Scouting Bureau]] (CSB) named him the WHL's top prospect in their preliminary rankings.<ref>{{citenews|title=Crosby, Brule head NHL CSB rankings|url=http://www.tsn.ca/story/print/?id=104862|accessdate=2011-03-11|date=2004-11-17|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}</ref> By the end of the season, Brul<U+00E9> was ranked fourth overall by the ISS and fifth among North American skaters by the CSB.<ref>{{cite news|title=ISS Top 15 Prospects for the 2005 NHL Draft|url=http://www.hockeysfuture.com/articles/7785/iss_top15_prospects_for_the2005_nhl_draft/|accessdate=2011-03-11|date=2005-07-18|publisher=HockeysFuture.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=2005 Entry Draft Rankings|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/page.htm?id=26400|accessdate=2011-03-11|date=2005-07-25|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]}}</ref> At the time of his draft, he was touted as an offensively skilled player with a competitive and physical edge.<ref name=bruiser>{{citenews|title=Blue Jackets' No. 1 choice a bruiser|url=http://news.google.ca/newspapers?id=ZEZIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=2IEMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4065,6207906&dq=gilbert+brule&hl=en|accessdate=2011-03-11|date=2005-07-31|publisher=''[[The Vindicator]]''}}</ref> The ISS scouted him as an "outstanding skater with great vision on the ice...a natural goalscorer."<ref name=bruiser/>

Brul<U+00E9> made the Blue Jackets' lineup in his first NHL training camp and signed with the club to a three-year, entry-level contract on October&nbsp;3,&nbsp;2005.<ref>{{citenews|title=Brule signs on with Blue Jackets|url=http://www.tsn.ca/nfl/story/?id=133083http://www.tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=138647|accessdate=2010-03-19|date=2005-10-03|publisher=[[CBC Sports]]}}</ref> He made his NHL debut against the [[Washington Capitals]] in the Blue Jackets' season opener two days later, notching an assist on a goal by [[Dan Fritsche]] in a 3<U+2013>1 loss.<ref>{{citenews|title=National Hockey League Game Capsules|url=http://www.ktvu.com/nhl/5064113/detail.html|accessdate=2010-03-19|date=2005-10-05|publisher=[[KTVU]]}}</ref> The following game, he suffered a [[sternum fracture|fractured sternum]] after receiving a hit from [[Calgary Flames]] defenceman [[Roman Hamrl<U+00ED>k]] on October&nbsp;7.<ref name=sternum>{{citenews|title=Brule absent au moins six semaines|url=http://www.rds.ca/hockey/chroniques/189824.html|accessdate=2011-03-11|date=2005-10-12|publisher=[[R<U+00E9>seau des sports]]}}</ref>  After missing&nbsp;17 games, he returned to the lineup on November&nbsp;20.<ref name=tsn/> Brul<U+00E9> scored his first NHL career goal that night against [[Phoenix Coyotes]], his team's lone tally in a 5<U+2013>1 loss, beating goaltender [[David LeNeveu]] with a shot from the left offensive zone faceoff circle.<ref>{{cite news|title=Columbus Blue Jackets 1, Phoenix Coyotes 5 Final|url=http://bluejackets.nhl.com/club/recap.htm?id=2005020311|accessdate=2011-03-11|date=2005-11-20|publisher=[[Columbus Blue Jackets]]}}</ref> Ten days later, he suffered his second injury in as many months, breaking his leg during a game against the [[Minnesota Wild]].<ref name="broken leg">{{citeweb|title=Columbus rookie C Brule out with broken leg|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/hockey/nhl/2005-12-01-roundup_x.htm|accessdate=2008-11-03|date=2005-12-01|publisher=''[[USA Today]]''}}</ref>

Upon recovering, he was returned to the WHL on January&nbsp;13,&nbsp;2006.<ref>{{citenews|title=Stirling fired by Islanders in second season as coach|url=http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/s_413128.html|accessdate=2010-03-19|date=2006-01-13|work=[[Pittsburgh Tribune-Review]]}}</ref>  By re-assigning Brul<U+00E9> before he played 10&nbsp;NHL games, the Blue Jackets retained the first year of his rookie contract.<ref>{{Citenews|title=Jackets getting hang of obstruction rule|url=http://www.dispatch.com/live/contentbe/dispatch/2006/01/05/20060105-E4-02.html|accessdate=2010-03-19|date=2006-01-05|publisher=''[[Columbus Dispatch]]''}}</ref> Another strong factor in the decision to return him to junior was the acquisition of centre [[Sergei Fedorov]], making Brul<U+00E9> expendable.<ref>{{Citenews|title=Once Brule heals, Jackets face decision|url=http://www.dispatch.com/live/contentbe/dispatch/2006/01/11/20060111-C5-02.html|accessdate=2010-03-19|date=2006-01-11|publisher=''[[Columbus Dispatch]]''|author=Aaron Portzline}}</ref> Returning to the Giants, Brul<U+00E9> scored at a near-goal-a-game pace.  He was named WHL Player of the Week on February&nbsp;20,&nbsp;2006, after recording 5&nbsp;goals and 10&nbsp;points in 3&nbsp;Giants wins.<ref>{{Citenews|title=Hockey: Short-handed Silvertips win 3 in row, extend lead|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/hockey/2002819968_silvertips22n.html|accessdate=2010-03-19|date=2006-02-23|publisher=''[[Seattle Times]]''|author=Jim Riley}}</ref>  He was later chosen as WHL Player of the Month for February with 12&nbsp;goals and 23&nbsp;points in 13&nbsp;games.<ref name=feb>{{citeweb|title=Brule named WHL Player of the Month|url=http://www.hockeysfuture.com/articles/8403/brule_named_whl_player_of_the_month/|accessdate=2008-11-03|publisher=HockeysFuture.com}}</ref>  Completing the season with 23&nbsp;goals and 38&nbsp;points in 27&nbsp;games, he earned WHL Second All-Star Team honours.<ref name=tsn>{{citeweb|title=Gilbert Brule|url=http://tsn.ca/nhl/teams/players/bio/?name=Gilbert+Brule|accessdate=2009-10-14|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}</ref> In the opening round of the WHL playoffs, Brul<U+00E9> was named WHL and CHL Player of the Week by scoring four goals and seven points over three games against the [[Prince George Cougars]].<ref name=chlpow>{{citenews|title=Gilbert Brule Named the CHL Player of the Week|url=http://www.hockeysfuture.com/articles/8557/gilbert_brule_named_the_chl_player_of_the_week/|accessdate=2010-03-19|date=2006-04-05|publisher=Hockey's Future}}</ref>  He received his second WHL and CHL Player of the Week honour during the WHL Finals against the [[Moose Jaw Warriors]] on May&nbsp;10, having accumulated five goals and nine points in two games.<ref name=chlpow2/>  His award-winning week included a three-goal, four-point performance in Game&nbsp;1 of the series <U+2013> a 7<U+2013>5 win for the Giants.<ref name=chlpow2>{{citenews|title=Gilbert Brule Named the CHL Player of the Week|url=http://www.hockeysfuture.com/article.php?sid=8726|accessdate=2010-03-19|date=2006-05-10|publisher=Hockey's Future}}</ref> He went on to lead the WHL in scoring with 30&nbsp;points in 18&nbsp;games to earn the [[airBC Trophy]] as playoff MVP, helping the Giants to their first [[Ed Chynoweth Cup|President's Cup]] as WHL champions.<ref>{{citeweb|title=The Ed Chynoweth Cup|url=http://www.whl.ca/page/the-ed-chynoweth-cup|accessdate=2011-03-11|publisher=[[Western Hockey League]]}}</ref>

Advancing to the [[2006 Memorial Cup]],{{#tag:ref|Winners of the three leagues that constitute the Canadian Hockey League go on to compete in the Memorial Cup for the national major junior championship; a fourth team participates as tournament hosts.|group=notes}} the Giants tied for third out of four teams after the round-robin. Requiring a tie-breaker game to determine who would play in the semi-final, Brul<U+00E9> recorded five points (two goals, three assists) against the [[Peterborough Petes]], one point short of the tournament single-game record, in a 6<U+2013>0 win.<ref>{{Citenews|title=For Petes sake, what was that?|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Hockey/Junior/2006/05/26/1599147-sun.html|accessdate=2010-03-21|date=2006-05-26|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> The Giants were subsequently eliminated in the semi-final by the [[Moncton Wildcats]] 3<U+2013>1.<ref name=moncton/>  Brul<U+00E9> registered the only Giants goal in the game.<ref name=moncton>{{citenews|title=Moncton in Memorial Cup final|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/story/2006/05/26/wildcats-giants-memorialcup.html|accessdate=2010-03-21|date=2006-05-26|publisher=[[CBC Sports]]}}</ref> Finishing with 12&nbsp;points in 5&nbsp;games, Brul<U+00E9> earned the [[Ed Chynoweth Trophy]] as the national tournament's leading scorer. He was also named to the Memorial Cup All-Star Team,<ref name=tsn/> alongside Giants teammate [[Paul Albers]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Paul Albers|url=http://tsn.ca/nhl/teams/players/bio/?id=5599|accessdate=2011-03-11|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}</ref>

[[Image:Gilbert Brule Giants Ring of Honour.jpg|thumb|right|Brul<U+00E9>'s Ring of Honour banner on display at the [[Pacific Coliseum]].]]
Four-and-a-half years after his junior career, the club honoured him in a ceremony prior to a game against the [[Kamloops Blazers]] on January&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2011, as part of "Gilbert Brul<U+00E9> Night". Brul<U+00E9> was the fourth alumnus added to the club's Ring of Honour, commemorating the team's best players; a plaque was unveiled inside the stadium bearing his name and the number 17 he wore on his jersey as a Giant.<ref>{{cite news|title=Giants win fifth straight in a mismatch|url=http://www.vancouverobserver.com/blogs/face-off/2011/01/29/giants-win-fifth-straight-mismatch|accessdate=2011-07-21|date=2011-01-29|work=[[Vancouver Observer]]|author=Kurylo, Jason}}</ref> At the end of the Giants' [[2010<U+2013>11 WHL season]], they released their fan-voted "Top 10 Giants of the Decade", which listed Brul<U+00E9> at #2, behind [[Milan Lucic]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Top 10 Giants of the Decade|url=http://www.faceoff.com/story.html?id=02972772-5ddc-4918-9ed9-c27cbbf216f0|accessdate=2011-07-20|publisher=[[Vancouver Giants]]}}</ref>

===Columbus Blue Jackets===
Still eligible for junior, Brul<U+00E9> made the Blue Jackets' roster for the [[2006<U+2013>07 NHL season|2006<U+2013>07 season]]. A month into the campaign, he was assured by general manager [[Doug MacLean]] that he would not be returned to the Giants as he had been the previous season.<ref>{{Citenews|title=Brule told he can relax|url=http://www.dispatch.com/live/contentbe/dispatch/2006/10/15/20061015-E12-02.html|accessdate=2010-03-21|date=2006-10-15|publisher=''[[Columbus Dispatch]]''|author=Aaron Portzline}}</ref> He was scratched several times under head coach [[Gerard Gallant]], but after Gallant was replaced by [[Ken Hitchcock]] in late-November, he began receiving more playing time.<ref name=hitchcock>{{citenews|title=Hitchcock's words give Brule extra motivation|url=http://www.dispatch.com/live/contentbe/dispatch/2006/11/28/20061128-C1-00.html|accessdate=2010-04-12|date=2006-11-28|publisher=''[[Columbus Dispatch]]''|author=Aaron Portzline}}</ref> Playing mostly on the [[line (ice hockey)|fourth line]] in his rookie season,<ref>{{citenews|title=Blue Jackets: Brule's streaky play didn't live up to billing|url=http://www.dispatch.com/live/contentbe/dispatch/2006/11/28/20061128-C1-00.html|accessdate=2010-03-21|date=2006-11-28|publisher=''[[Columbus Dispatch]]''|author=Michael Arace}}</ref> he averaged 10&nbsp;minutes of ice time per game.<ref>{{citenews|title=Jackets' first-round draft whiffs are evident|url=http://www.dispatch.com/live/content/bluejackets/stories/2007/11/21/arace21.ART_ART_11-21-07_C1_968HS63.html?sid=101|accessdate=2010-03-21|date=2007-11-21|publisher=''[[Columbus Dispatch]]''|author=Michael Arace}}</ref> He went on to tally 19&nbsp;points (9&nbsp;goals and 10&nbsp;assists) over 78&nbsp;games in his first full NHL season.

During [[2007<U+2013>08 NHL season|his second NHL season]], Brul<U+00E9> recorded 9&nbsp;points (1&nbsp;goal and 8&nbsp;assists) over 61&nbsp;games with the Blue Jackets.  He was sent down to the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) in January&nbsp;2008 for a month-long assignment as his play struggled,<ref>{{citeweb|title=Jackets notebook: Brule to stay with Syracuse|url=http://www.dispatch.com/live/content/bluejackets/stories/2008/01/22/jackets_notes22.ART_ART_01-22-08_C5_5094IOG.html?sid=101|accessdate=2008-11-03|date=2008-01-22|publisher=''[[Columbus Dispatch]]''}}</ref><ref name=tsn/> notching 5&nbsp;goals and 10&nbsp;points in 16&nbsp;games with the Blue Jackets' minor league affiliate, the [[Syracuse Crunch]]. At the end of the Blue Jackets' regular season, Brul<U+00E9> was re-assigned to Syracuse for the club's [[Calder Cup]] playoff run. Helping the Crunch advance to the second round, he recorded 2&nbsp;goals and 5&nbsp;points over 13&nbsp;post-season games.

===Edmonton Oilers===
In the 2008 off-season, Brul<U+00E9> was traded to the [[Edmonton Oilers]] for forward [[Raffi Torres]] on July&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2008.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Oilers trade Torres to Blue Jackets, Pitkanen to Hurricanes|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/news/story?id=3469127|accessdate=2008-11-03|date=2008-07-01|publisher=ESPN}}</ref> He was one of the final cuts in his first training camp with the Oilers and was assigned to the [[Springfield Falcons]], Edmonton's AHL affiliate.<ref name=tsn/>  On October&nbsp;17,&nbsp;2008, he suffered a knee-on-knee hit from opposing defenceman [[Adam McQuaid]] during a game against the [[Providence Bruins]], causing him to miss several contests injured.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Brule takes time to recover from knee-on-knee hit|url=http://www.canada.com/edmontonjournal/news/business/story.html?id=beae8e66-fb91-4d43-a445-c65cd414e310|accessdate=2008-11-03|date=2008-10-20|publisher=''[[Edmonton Journal]]''}}</ref>  During a call-up to the NHL later in the season, Brul<U+00E9> scored his first goal with the Oilers on January&nbsp;11,&nbsp;2009, in a 2<U+2013>1 win against the [[St. Louis Blues]].<ref>{{Citeweb|title=Gagner blast gives Oilers much-needed win|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/story/2009/01/11/gagner-oilers-blues.html|accessdate=2009-01-12|date=2009-01-12|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}</ref> He was re-assigned to Springfield 10&nbsp;days later.<ref name=tsn/> Finishing the season with 3&nbsp;points in 11&nbsp;games with the Oilers and 24&nbsp;points in 39&nbsp;games with the Falcons, he was re-signed by Edmonton in the off-season to a one-year, two-way contract on August&nbsp;12,&nbsp;2009.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Oilers ink Smid to two-year deal; sign Brule and Stone|url=http://tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=287501|accessdate=2009-08-12|date=2009-08-12|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}</ref>

Brul<U+00E9> began the [[2009<U+2013>10 NHL season|2009<U+2013>10 season]] as the Oilers' fourth-line centre out of training camp.<ref>{{citenews|title=Pouliot, Lowe share the pain|url=http://www.faceoff.com/hockey/nhlnews/story.html?id=12e7ca15-ab42-4836-912b-ace686944b82|accessdate=2010-04-12|date=2009-09-29|publisher=''[[Edmonton Journal]]''|author=Jim Matheson}}</ref> With improved play and the injury of first-line winger [[Ales Hemsky]],<ref>{{citenews|title=Brule's star shines with Oilers|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Hockey/NHL/Edmonton/2009/11/30/11978186-sun.html|accessdate=2010-04-12|date=2009-11-30|publisher=[[Sun Media Corporation]]|author=Derek Van Diest}}</ref><ref>{{citenews|title=Smyth's impact|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/fantasy/2009/12/02/smyth-s-impact/|accessdate=2010-04-11|date=2009-12-02|publisher=[[Rogers Sportsnet]]|author=Chris Nichols}}</ref> Brul<U+00E9> moved up the Oilers' depth chart and recorded his best statistical season in the NHL. However, after suffering from a recurring [[influenza|flu]] throughout the campaign, which sidelined him for a combined 11&nbsp;games,<ref name=tsn/> he suffered a [[sprained ankle|high-ankle sprain]] during a game against the [[Dallas Stars]] on April&nbsp;2,&nbsp;2010; following a collision with opposing forward [[Brian Sutherby]], his skate got jammed underneath goaltender [[Kari Lehtonen]]'s pad. The injury sidelined him for the remaining week of the campaign.<ref name="ankle sprain">{{citenews|title=Brule's hard work comes to premature end|url=http://www.vancouversun.com/sports/Brule+season+Oilers+prepare+battle+Phoenix/2761146/story.html|accessdate=2010-04-12|date=2010-04-04|publisher=''[[Edmonton Journal]]''|author=Jim Matheson}}</ref> He finished the season with a career-high 17&nbsp;goals, 20&nbsp;assists and 37&nbsp;points in 65&nbsp;games, third in team-scoring.<ref>{{citeweb|title=2009-2010 - Regular Season - Edmonton Oilers - All Skaters - Summary - Total Points|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/playerstats.htm?fetchKey=20102EDMSASAll&sort=points&viewName=summary|accessdate=2010-04-12|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]}}</ref> Becoming a [[restricted free agent]] in the 2010 off-season, Brul<U+00E9> filed for [[arbitration]] with the Oilers after failing to come to terms on a new contract. The two sides managed to avoid their arbitration hearing by signing a two-year, $3.7&nbsp;million deal on July&nbsp;27,&nbsp;2010.<ref>{{citenews|title=Brule avoids arbitration, signs 2-year deal with Oilers|url=http://tsn.ca/nhl/story/?id=328687|accessdate=2010-07-27|date=2010-07-27|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}</ref>

After staying healthy through the first three months of the [[2010<U+2013>11 NHL season|2010<U+2013>11 season]], Brul<U+00E9> suffered continued injury problems for the rest of the campaign. After being sidelined with a stomach virus for four games, he suffered an abdominal injury the following month and missed 23&nbsp;additional contests.<ref name=tsn/><ref>{{Cite news|title=Hemsky read to return|url=http://www.torontosun.com/sports/myoilers/2010/12/26/16676926.html|accessdate=2011-07-21|date=2010-12-26|work=[[Edmonton Sun]]|author=Van Deist, Derek}}</ref> After returning to the lineup, he sustained a concussion during a game against the [[Pittsburgh Penguins]] on March&nbsp;13,&nbsp;2011.<ref>{{cite news|title=Brule back ine lineup|url=http://www.lfpress.com/sports/hockey/2011/03/31/17826031.html|accessdate=2011-05-07|date=2011-03-31|work=[[London Free Press]]|publisher=QMI Agency|author=Van Diest, Derek}}</ref> In total, Brul<U+00E9> missed 39&nbsp;games with injuries in 2010<U+2013>11, limiting him to 7&nbsp;goals and 2&nbsp;assists.

On June&nbsp;24,&nbsp;2011, it was reported that Brul<U+00E9> had been traded along with a fourth-round draft pick to the [[Los Angeles Kings]] in exchange for forward [[Ryan Smyth]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Oilers re-acquire Smyth from Kings: report|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/story/2011/06/24/sp-nhl-lakings-edm.html|accessdate=2011-06-24|date=2011-06-24|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|agency=Canadian Press}}</ref> Due to health concerns, the deal never officially materialized as Brul<U+00E9> had not yet been cleared to play following his concussion (under league rules, an injured player can be traded but cannot be bought out which is what the Kings had planned on doing). Furthermore, Kings general manager [[Dean Lombardi]] made it apparent to the media that the team wanted someone with a smaller salary cap hit.<ref>{{cite news|title=Smyth trade to Oilers has 'broken down' over salary cap concerns|url=http://www.edmontonjournal.com/sports/Smyth+trade+Oilers+stalled+concerns+about+Brule+health/5006333/story.html?cid=megadrop_story|date=2011-06-25|work=[[Edmonton Journal]]|agency=Canadian Press}}</ref> The Oilers ultimately acquired Smyth in exchange for forward [[Colin Fraser]] and a seventh-round pick in the [[2012 NHL Entry Draft|2012 draft]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Kings trade Ryan Smyth to Edmonton for Colin Fraser, seventh-round draft pick|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-kings-smyth-20110627,0,7216884.story|accessdate=2011-06-27|date=2011-06-26|work=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|author=Elliott, Helene}}</ref>

==International play==
{{MedalTableTop}}
{{MedalCountry|{{ih|CAN}}}}
{{MedalSport|[[Ice hockey]]}}
{{MedalCompetition|[[Ivan Hlinka Memorial Tournament|U18 Junior World Cup]]}}
{{MedalGold| [[2004 U-18 Junior World Cup|2004 Czech Republic]]|}}
{{MedalCompetition|[[World U17 Hockey Challenge]]}}
{{MedalSilver|[[2004 World U-17 Hockey Challenge|2004 Canada]]|}}
{{MedalBottom}}

Brul<U+00E9> made his international debut with [[Hockey Canada]] representing Team Pacific at the 2004 [[World U17 Hockey Challenge]] in [[Newfoundland and Labrador|Newfoundland]].  During the semi-final, he scored a goal and three assists, leading Team Pacific to a win against the [[USA Hockey|United States]]. His efforts earned him his third player of the game award of the tournament.<ref>{{citeweb|title=2004 World U17 Hockey Challenge|url=http://www.hockeycanada.ca/index.php/ci_id/9455/la_id/1.htm|accessdate=2008-12-14|publisher=[[Hockey Canada]]}}</ref> In the gold medal game, Team Pacific lost to Team Ontario 5<U+2013>2, earning silver. Later that year, he represented Team Canada in the 2004 [[Ivan Hlinka Memorial Tournament|U18 Junior World Cup]] as an [[alternate captain (hockey)|alternate captain]].  Brul<U+00E9> helped lead Team Canada to gold, scoring the [[game winning goal]] in the championship match, a 4<U+2013>1 win against the [[Czech Ice Hockey Association|Czech Republic]].<ref>{{Citeweb|title=Canada's national under-18 summer team captures gold at 2004 junior world cup|url=http://www.hockeycanada.ca/index.php?ci_id=11030&la_id=1|accessdate=2008-12-14|publisher=[[Hockey Canada]]}}</ref>

The following year, Brul<U+00E9> participated in the [[Canada national junior hockey team|Canadian national junior team]]'s summer development camp in preparation for the [[2006 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2006 World Junior Championships]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Red 3 White 4|url=http://hockeycanada.ca/index.php/ci_id/16938/la_id/1.htm|accessdate=2011-07-21|date=2005-08-13|publisher=[[Hockey Canada]]}}</ref> At the time of the final roster selection in December 2005, however, Brul<U+00E9> was recovering from a leg injury, suffered during NHL play with the Blue Jackets.<ref name=tsn/> He was invited to the team's summer camp again in 2006, but declined, choosing to focus instead on making the roster for Columbus.<ref>{{citenews|title=Juniors inquire about NHLers|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/thestar/access/1171169311.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Nov+30%2C+2006&author=&pub=The+Guelph+Mercury&desc=Juniors+inquire+about+NHLers&pqatl=google|accessdate=2011-03-11|date=2006-11-30|publisher=''Guelph Mercury''}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Brul<U+00E9> was born in [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]], later moving to [[North Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], during his childhood. He had a sister named Leah who passed away at the age of 12 from [[cerebral palsy]]. Brul<U+00E9> was nine years old at the time of his sister's death and later had her name tattooed on his left wrist.<ref name="trip to ahl">{{citenews|title=Trip to AHL enhances Brule's NHL future|url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=370259|accessdate=2011-03-11|date=2008-01-14|publisher=[[National Hockey League]]}}</ref> Despite growing up in both Edmonton and Vancouver, Brul<U+00E9> was a childhood fan of the [[Los Angeles Kings]].<ref>{{Citenews|title=Hitchcock's words give Brule extra motivation|url=http://www.columbusdispatch.com/bluejackets/bluejackets.php?story=dispatch/2006/11/28/20061128-C1-00.html|accessdate=2010-03-21|date=2006-11-28|publisher=''[[Columbus Dispatch]]''|author=Aaron Portzline}}</ref>

In May&nbsp;2010, Brul<U+00E9> donated $10,000 to a fund assisting an Edmonton boy suffering from [[Lymphangioma|lymphatic cystic hydroma]]. The money was allocated to a costly surgery to be performed in [[New York]], which doctors in Canada were unable to perform.<ref>{{Citenews|title=NHLer helps out youngster's surgery|url=http://cnews.canoe.ca/CNEWS/Good_News/2010/05/21/14032146.html|accessdate=2010-05-21|date=2010-05-21|publisher=''[[The Edmonton Sun]]''|author=Alyssa Noel}}</ref> Brul<U+00E9> received further media attention a year later for picking up a pair of hitchhikers who turned out to be [[U2]] frontman [[Bono]] and his assistant in a [[West Vancouver]] neighbourhood on May&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2011. In return, Brul<U+00E9> was given backstage passes for him, as well as his girlfriend and mother, for U2's concert in Edmonton on the next day. During the show, Bono thanked Brul<U+00E9> for the ride.<ref>{{Citenews|title=Oiler Brule gave life to hitchhiking Bono|url=http://www.edmontonjournal.com/Oiler+Brule+gave+lift+hitchhiking+Bono/4877705/story.html?cid=dlvr.it-twitter-edmontonjournal||accessdate=2011-06-01|date=2011-06-01|work=[[Edmonton Journal]]|author=Ben Gelinas}}</ref>

